NFLX Stock Price Evolution

1. Annualized Return (CAGR)

In[10]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data and clean 'Adj Close'
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv")
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df.set_index('Date', inplace=True)
df['Adj Close'] = df['Adj Close'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)  # Clean and convert

# Recalculate CAGR
start_price = df['Adj Close'].iloc[0]
end_price = df['Adj Close'].iloc[-1]
years = (df.index[-1] - df.index[0]).days / 365.25
cagr = (end_price / start_price) ** (1/years) - 1

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['Adj Close'], color='navy')
plt.title('NFLX CAGR (20022025)', fontsize=14)
plt.annotate(f'CAGR: {cagr:.2%}', xy=(0.7, 0.1), xycoords='axes fraction', fontsize=12)
plt.savefig("NFLX CACR.png")
plt.show()

2. Annual High/Low Prices & Milestones

In[4]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv")

# Clean numeric columns (use errors='coerce' to handle invalid values)
numeric_cols = ['Open ', 'High', 'Low', 'Close', 'Adj Close', 'Volume']
for col in numeric_cols:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col].str.replace(',', ''), errors='coerce')  # Replace commas and convert

# Drop rows with NaN (if needed)
df = df.dropna(subset=numeric_cols)

# Convert date and set index
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# --------------------------------------------------------
# Question 2: Annual High/Low Prices (Corrected Code)
# --------------------------------------------------------
# Use 'YE' instead of 'Y'
annual_high_low = df.resample('YE').agg({'High': 'max', 'Low': 'min'}).reset_index()
annual_high_low['Year'] = annual_high_low['Date'].dt.year

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.bar(annual_high_low['Year'] - 0.2, annual_high_low['High'], width=0.4, label='High', color='green')
plt.bar(annual_high_low['Year'] + 0.2, annual_high_low['Low'], width=0.4, label='Low', color='red')
plt.title('Annual High/Low Prices', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Price ($)', fontsize=12)
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(annual_high_low['Year'][::2])
plt.savefig("Annual prices.png")
plt.show()

3. Seasonal Patterns

In[11]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data and set datetime index
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv")
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Clean 'Close' column (if needed)
df['Close'] = df['Close'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)

# Calculate returns
df['Return'] = df['Close'].pct_change(fill_method=None)

# Resample quarterly
quarterly_returns = df['Return'].resample('QE').mean()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
quarterly_returns.plot(title='Quarterly Average Returns', color='navy', linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel('Quarter', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Return (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.savefig("seasonal patterns.png")
plt.show()

4. Volatility During Crises

In[12]:
# Define crisis periods
crisis_periods = {
    '2008 Recession': ('2007-12-01', '2009-06-01'),
    'COVID-19': ('2020-02-01', '2020-04-01')
}

# Calculate volatility (std of returns)
volatility = {}
for crisis, (start, end) in crisis_periods.items():
    mask = (df.index >= start) & (df.index <= end)
    volatility[crisis] = df.loc[mask, 'Return'].std()

# Compare to non-crisis period
volatility['Stable Period'] = df.loc[~df.index.isin(pd.date_range(start='2007-12-01', end='2020-04-01')), 'Return'].std()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(volatility.keys(), volatility.values(), color=['firebrick', 'darkorange', 'steelblue'])
plt.title('Volatility During Crises vs Stable Periods', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Standard Deviation of Returns', fontsize=12)
plt.savefig("volatility.png")
plt.show()

5. Average True Range (ATR)

In[21]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv", parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')

# Clean 'High' and 'Low' columns
df['High'] = df['High'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)
df['Low'] = df['Low'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)

# Calculate True Range (TR) and ATR
df['TR'] = df['High'] - df['Low']
df['ATR'] = df['TR'].rolling(14).mean()

# Plot ATR
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['ATR'], color='darkcyan', label='14-Day ATR')
plt.title('Average True Range (ATR)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('ATR', fontsize=12)
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.savefig("average true range.png")
plt.show()

8. High-Volume Days Close vs Open

In[43]:
import pandas as pd

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv")

# Clean and convert 'Volume' to numeric
df['Volume'] = pd.to_numeric(
    df['Volume'].astype(str).str.replace(',', ''),  # Remove commas and convert to float
    errors='coerce'  # Convert invalid entries (e.g., "7:1 Stock Splits") to NaN
)

# Drop rows with NaN in 'Volume'
df = df.dropna(subset=['Volume'])
# Identify high-volume days (top 10%)
high_volume = df[df['Volume'] > df['Volume'].quantile(0.9)]

# Option 1: Use 'Open ' with space
up_days = (high_volume['Close'] > high_volume['Open ']).sum()

# Option 2 (after renaming): Use 'Open' without space
# up_days = (high_volume['Close'] > high_volume['Open']).sum()

down_days = len(high_volume) - up_days

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.pie([up_days, down_days], labels=['Up Days', 'Down Days'], autopct='%1.1f%%', colors=['limegreen', 'tomato'])
plt.title('High-Volume Days: Close vs Open', fontsize=14)
plt.savefig("volume days.png")
plt.show()

9. How do NFLXs average daily returns vary by day of the week?

In[36]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv", parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')
df['Adj Close'] = df['Adj Close'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)  # Clean data

# Calculate daily returns (explicitly disable fill)
df['Daily Return'] = df['Adj Close'].pct_change(fill_method=None) * 100

# Extract weekday name
df['Weekday'] = df.index.day_name()

# Group by weekday and calculate mean return
weekday_returns = df.groupby('Weekday')['Daily Return'].mean().reindex(
    ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday']
)

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
weekday_returns.plot(kind='bar', color='skyblue', edgecolor='black')
plt.title('Average Daily Returns by Weekday (NFLX)', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Day of the Week', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Return (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.savefig("average daily returns.png")
plt.show()

11. Moving Averages (50 vs 200-Day)

In[41]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv", parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')

# Clean the 'Close' column (remove commas and convert to float)
df['Close'] = df['Close'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)

# Calculate moving averages
df['MA50'] = df['Close'].rolling(50).mean()
df['MA200'] = df['Close'].rolling(200).mean()

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['Close'], label='Close Price', alpha=0.5)
plt.plot(df['MA50'], label='50-Day MA', color='orange')
plt.plot(df['MA200'], label='200-Day MA', color='purple')
plt.title('NFLX Moving Averages (50-Day vs 200-Day)')
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("moving averages.png")
plt.show()

12. RSI Effectiveness

In[49]:
# Calculate RSI
delta = df['Close'].diff()
gain = delta.clip(lower=0)
loss = -delta.clip(upper=0)
avg_gain = gain.rolling(14).mean()
avg_loss = loss.rolling(14).mean()
rs = avg_gain / avg_loss
df['RSI'] = 100 - (100 / (1 + rs))

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(df['RSI'], color='blue')
plt.axhline(70, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Overbought')
plt.axhline(30, color='green', linestyle='--', label='Oversold')
plt.title('Relative Strength Index (RSI)', fontsize=14)
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("rsi effectiveness.png")
plt.show()

13. Largest Single-Day Gains/Losses

In[50]:
import pandas as pd

# Load data and clean the 'Close' column (if needed)
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv", parse_dates=['Date'], index_col='Date')
df['Close'] = df['Close'].str.replace(',', '').astype(float)  # Remove commas if present

# Calculate daily returns (disable fill_method)
df['Daily Return'] = df['Close'].pct_change(fill_method=None) * 100

# Drop NaN values (optional)
df = df.dropna(subset=['Daily Return'])

# Proceed with analysis or visualization
df['Daily Return'] = df['Close'].pct_change() * 100
top_gains = df.nlargest(5, 'Daily Return')
top_losses = df.nsmallest(5, 'Daily Return')

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(top_gains.index.strftime('%Y-%m-%d'), top_gains['Daily Return'], color='limegreen', label='Gains')
plt.barh(top_losses.index.strftime('%Y-%m-%d'), top_losses['Daily Return'], color='tomato', label='Losses')
plt.title('Top 5 Daily Gains & Losses', fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Return (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.legend()
plt.savefig("daily gains and lossespng.png")
plt.show()

14. Recovery from Drawdowns

In[46]:
import pandas as pd

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("Netflix Inc. (NFLX) Stock Price 2002-2025.csv")

# Clean 'Close' column
df['Close'] = pd.to_numeric(
    df['Close'].astype(str).str.replace(',', ''),  # Force string and remove commas
    errors='coerce'  # Convert invalid entries to NaN
)

# Drop rows with NaN (if needed)
df = df.dropna(subset=['Close'])

# Proceed to calculate returns
df['Return'] = df['Close'].pct_change(fill_method=None)
cum_returns = (1 + df['Return']).cumprod()
peak = cum_returns.expanding(min_periods=1).max()
drawdown = (cum_returns - peak) / peak

# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.fill_between(drawdown.index, drawdown, color='red', alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Cumulative Drawdowns', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Drawdown (%)', fontsize=12)
plt.savefig("cumulative drawdowns.png")
plt.show()
